\subsection*{Summary basic information} %emw14Jun2026: this is not a subheader you can have in a paper. 
%emw14Jun2026: once you're writing full text you have to drop 'Wildchrokie'
Wildchrokie includes four deciduous tree species from four sites with leaf phenology data spanning three years (2018 to 2020) for a total of \Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} leafout and 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)} budset observations, yielding 
\Sexpr{nrow(emp)} complete growing seasons (GS) for 
\Sexpr{length(unique(emp$treeid))} individuals. At the common garden location, the mean summer temperature was similar across years with 2019 being the coolest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2019)]}$^\circ$C), 2020 the hottest 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2020)]}$^\circ$C), and 2018 in between 
(\Sexpr{wcjja$tmeanmean[which(wcjja$year == 2018)]}$^\circ$C). There was no drought for those three years, except for in 2020, where a moderate summer drought ramped up to a severe drought in September.%emw14Jun2026: defined how? And which months were moderate? You also need this in the methods. 
 The calendar and thermal seasons ranged from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$pgsGSL)} days and 
\Sexpr{round(min(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$pgsGSL)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$pgsGSL)} days and \Sexpr{round(max(emp$pgsGDD5),1)} GDD ({\Ainc} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$pgsGSL)]}). The earliest leafout  %emw14Jun2026: not day of year -- that's a number. 
was 
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.min(emp$leafout)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$leafout)]}) and the latest,
\Sexpr{emp$loCal[which.max(emp$leafout)]} (also {\Ainc}, but in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$leafout)]}). The earliest budset day of year was 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.min(emp$budset)]} ({\Ball} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$budset)]}) and the latest, 
\Sexpr{emp$bsCal[which.max(emp$budset)]} ({\Ainc} in
\Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$budset)]}). Finally, annual ring widths across years varied from 
\Sexpr{min(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Ball} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.min(emp$lengthMM)]}) to 
\Sexpr{max(emp$lengthMM)} mm ({\Bpop} in \Sexpr{emp$year[which.max(emp$lengthMM)]}) (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotayear}). 

