\subsection*{Did a later start and end of season increase growth?}
%emw14Jun2026: I would try to sneak in some discussion to the results here! You may get told to take it out but I think it would help readers (and don't fully see the point of the rule):
Increased growth with longer seasons is often presumed to come from growth in the spring, since spring phenology has shifted much more than fall phenology. However, while we found that 
a longer calendar season increased growth for two species, only one also grew more with an earlier start of season ({\Ainc}: $\beta = $ 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$mean[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, $UI_{90}$
[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "A. incana")]}]) (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g) (Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}). However, {\Ball} which did not grow more with longer calendar season, grew less with an earlier start of season ($\beta = $ 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$mean[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, $UI_{90}$
[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p5[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_sos$p95[which(bspp_df2_sos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}]) (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}c and g) (Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table})---but more with a later end of season ($\beta = $ 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, $UI_{90}$
[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. alleghaniensis")]}]). Alongside {\Ball}, two other species grew more with a later end of season ({\Bpop}: $\beta = $ 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, $UI_{90}$
[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. populifolia")]}], and {\Bpap}:$\beta = $ 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$mean[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, $UI_{90}$
[\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p5[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}, 
\Sexpr{bspp_df2_eos$p95[which(bspp_df2_eos$spp_name %in% "B. papyrifera")]}]), with the latter being the only one of those three that also grew more with longer calendar season (Figure \ref{fig:wcmuplotbspp}d and h) (Table \ref{tab:wc_slope_table}). \\
  
The estimates were unchanged when using the full (SOS $n =$ %emw14Jun2026: this sentence just needs to be in the previous paragraph; you cannot have 1 sentence paragraph in sci papers. 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfullsos)} and $n =$ 
\Sexpr{nrow(empfulleos)}) or restricted datasets ($n=$ 
\Sexpr{nrow(emp)}) (Figure \ref{fig:wcSOSEOScomparison}a). 
  
